5. Lesson 5

  • In this lesson, we will focus on sales prediction (Time Series forecasting) analysis.

  • Time Series forecasting with Holt-Winters. Holt-Winters forecasting is a way to model and predict the behavior of a sequence of values over time—a time series. Holt-Winters is one of the most popular forecasting techniques for time series. Many other time series forecasting models exist such as ARIMA, TBATS, etc.

  • We will demonstrate Time Series forecasting with Holt-Winters model. Other forecasting models such as ARIMA and Seasonal ARIMA models will be used in the evaluation of data modelling.

5.1 Sales prediction analysis.

  • The objective (business goal) of this analysis is sales prediction for the next following 100 days afterwards the last day (2011-11-30) in the dataset of the online retail. The sales prediction is based on the data during 2009-12-01 and 2011-11-30.

  • There are no fixed rules for determining the duration of the forecast period. However, choosing a forecast period of 10 years, for example, will not be meaningful when individual cash flows can only reasonably be modeled for four years. The number of forecasting years is therefore to be limited by the “meaningfulness” of the individual yearly cash flows ahead. There are three typical methods of determining the forecast period. (Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecast_period_(finance))

    1. Based on company positioning
    2. Based on exit strategy
    3. Based on market characteristics

  • We are going to perform sales forecasting with below steps in this lesson:

    1. Data collection
    2. Data preparation for timeseries data, based on the data during 2009-12-01 and 2011-11-30.
    3. Separate the data into train set and test set
    4. Model Fitting with HoltWinters method
    5. Forecast Model
    6. Visualize the model
    7. Model Evaluation of HoltWinters model
    8. Accuracy test
    9. Sales forecasting on next 10 days of the online retail

5.1.1 Collect data

  • Reuse the dataset (filename: R_DA_Data_online_retail_II_clean.csv) which is created in lesson 1 and import it. Reference link of the dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Online+Retail+II
df.retail <- read.csv(file = 'R_DA_Data_online_retail_II_clean.csv', header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, strip.white = TRUE, sep = ",")
#data type of InvoiceDate is "chr" from csv format, we convert it back to date-time format by as.POSIXct() function.
df.retail$InvoiceDate <- as.POSIXct(df.retail$InvoiceDate)

5.1.2 Data preparation for modelling

  • In this section, we will focus on below tasks:

    1. Data cleaning
    2. Construct new features of the data used in sales prediction model.
    3. time series setup

5.1.2.1 Data cleaning

  1. Data cleaning is the process of identifying, correcting, or removing inaccurate raw data for downstream purposes. It is the process of transforming dirty data into reliable data that can be analyzed. The dataset (df.retail) we are going to use is already cleaned in lesson 1. We reuse the clean dataset.

5.1.2.2 Construct new features of the data used in sales prediction model.

    1. Define your target and time horizons: What do you want predict exactly? Sales of the next day given all previous days? Sales of the next month given only the previous 12 months? Sales at each hour of the day?
    2. Build an aggregated dataset: Aggregate sales for each day or month or other timespan depending on what you decided earlier.
# Hourly, daily and monthly split of date time for Invoice date

5.1.2.3 Time series setup

  1. Time series setup. Before we do anything regarding forecasting, we need to tell R that this data is a time series.

    • Frequency of a time series is the number of observations per unit of time. When using the time-series ts() function in R, the following choices for frequency should be used.
      1. Annual is 1
      2. Quarterly is 4
      3. Monthly is 12
      4. Weekly is 52
      5. If the frequency of observations is greater than once per week, then there is usually more than one way of handling the frequency. For example, data with daily observations might have a weekly seasonality (frequency=7) or an annual seasonality (frequency=365.25).
    • In this case, we set the parameter “frequency” in the time series by below steps:
      1. The data will be separated into two portions, training set and test set. We will fit the time series data with Holt-Winters method by training set without test set. The test data is used to evaluate its accuracy.
      2. Total number of records of the time series is 595
      3. Training set is 70% of the total records
      4. Total number of records of the training set is 416
      5. Total number of records of the test set is 179
      6. Therefore, the frequency is calculated by the records of the training set over 2, that is 416/2 = 208, because the training set will be fitted with Holt-Winters method and the time series (training set) should have at least 2 periods of the frequency. In short, the frequency cannot be set more than 208.
#Converting to a time series by ts() function
#syntax of ts(data, start, end, frequency)
#data: a vector of the observed time-series values. 
#start: the time of the first observation. Either a single number or a vector of two numbers 
#end: the time of the last observation. Either a single number or a vector of two numbers 
#frequency: the number of observations per unit of time (1=annual, 4=quartly, 12=monthly, etc.).
sales_ts_full <- ts(data = df.retail_sales_day$Total_sales, start = 1, frequency = 208)
#check the data type
class(sales_ts_full)
## [1] "ts"
str(sales_ts_full)
##  Time-Series [1:595] from 1 to 3.86: 43222 51387 65173 33257 9628 ...

5.1.3 Data modelling with testing and training data

  • When choosing models, it is common practice to separate the available data into two portions, training and test data.

    1. the training data is used to estimate any parameters of a forecasting method
    2. the test data is used to evaluate its accuracy. Because the test data is not used in determining the forecasts, it should provide a reliable indication of how well the model is likely to forecast on new data.

5.1.3.1 Partitioning dataset into training and test data.

  • Partitioning dataset into training and test data. To split a time series we need a vector that is a time series. After the splitting, the training and test data should also be a time series. To partition dataset into training and test data, we can follow below steps:

    1. The size of the test set is typically around 20%-40% of the total sample.
    2. We set the test set is 30% of the total sample in this example. That is, training set is 70% of the total sample.
    3. The forecast package supports head and tail functions for time series. This enables a very handy mechanism for creating train and test sets. All you have to do is provide the size of the training set.
    • Inspect the full data set. Total number of records of the full data set is 595.
#overview of the time series full dataset "sales_ts_full" which we created before.
str(sales_ts_full)
##  Time-Series [1:595] from 1 to 3.86: 43222 51387 65173 33257 9628 ...
#total number of records of the time series
round(length(sales_ts_full))
## [1] 595
  • Partitioning dataset into training and test data. Use first 70% data (training data) for forecasting, and remaining data (test data) to test accuracy.
library(forecast)
## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 4.1.3
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
# Training set
# Use first 70% data for forecasting
sales_ts_train <- head(sales_ts_full, round(length(sales_ts_full) * 0.7))

# Test set
# Use remaining data to test accuracy
h <- length(sales_ts_full) - length(sales_ts_train)
sales_ts_test <- tail(sales_ts_full, h)

  • We have split dataset into training and test data. Now let’s inspect the training set and test set.

    1. original full data: sales_ts_full
    2. training data (70% of the original full data): sales_ts_train
    3. test data (30% of the original full data): sales_ts_test

5.1.3.2 Fitting with Holt-Winters.

  • Holt-Winters forecasting is a way to model and predict the behavior of a sequence of values over time—a time series. Holt-Winters is one of the most popular forecasting techniques for time series.

  • Fitting with Holt-Winters. Before we predict values in the future, we’ll need to create a fit by the data. In the most basic method, we can simply call the Holt-Winters function and let R figure out the tuning parameters on it’s own. We also can tune the fit manually by setting tuning variables to see how the fit changes.

  • Syntax of HoltWinters(data, alpha, beta, gamma)

    1. data: An object of class ts (time series)
    2. alpha: the “base value”. Higher alpha puts more weight on the most recent observations.
    3. beta: the “trend value”. Higher beta means the trend slope is more dependent on recent trend slopes.
    4. gamma: the “seasonal component”. Higher gamma puts more weighting on the most recent seasonal cycles.
#Holt-Winters function and let R figure out the tuning parameters on it’s own
HW <- HoltWinters(sales_ts_train)

#Visually evaluate the fits to see of how well the HoltWinters model generalizes data similar to that with which it was trained.
plot(sales_ts_train, xlab="Time", ylab="Sales", main = "HoltWinters fits to our data")

#Blue line for Holt-Winters function with the tuning parameters on it’s own
lines(HW$fitted[,1], lty=1, lwd=3, col="blue")

5.1.3.3 Forecast Model and Visualize the model

  • Use forecast to model future values. forecast() function is a wrapper for predict that allows for more confidence intervals, makes plotting easier, and gives us tools to evaluate the quality of our predictions. Using our HW Holt-Winters fit from before, we can use forecast to make new predictions and include both 80% and 95% confidence intervals.

  • In our case, daily data is used for sales forecasting and we forecast sales on the next following 179 days (same as test data) from the training data.

  • Install package for forecasting time series

install.packages("forecast")
## Warning: package 'forecast' is in use and will not be installed
library("forecast")
# Using our HW Holt-Winters fit from before, we can use forecast to make new predictions and include both 80% and 95% confidence intervals.
#Syntax of forecast(object, h, level)
#object: a time series
#h: Number of periods for forecasting. In our case, daily data is used and we forecast sales on the next 179 days from the training data. Thus, h is 179.
#level: Confidence level for prediction intervals. Reference: https://towardsdatascience.com/how-confidence-and-prediction-intervals-work-4592019576d8
#0% confidence level means you have no faith at all that if you repeated the survey that you would get the same results. A 100% confidence level means there is no doubt at all that if you repeated the survey you would get the same results. 
HW_forecast <- forecast(HW, h=179, level=0)
#visualize our prediction:
plot(HW_forecast, xlab="Time", ylab="Sales")

#show the range of the forecast sales 
range(HW_forecast$x)
## [1]  3439.67 99203.62
#show the range of total sales of test data
range(sales_ts_test)
## [1]   5701.87 103238.68
  • Visualize our prediction with the test data. The prediction values are displayed by blue color, the test data (sales_ts_test) is red line.
autoplot(HW_forecast) + autolayer(sales_ts_test)+
  xlab("Time") +
  ylab("Total Sales") +
  guides(colour = guide_legend(title = "Test data"))

5.1.4 Evaluation of data modelling

  • In this section, we will use Holt-Winters, ARIMA and Seasonal ARIMA forecasting models together for the evaluation of data modelling. We will apply accuracy measures on these three forecast models to evaluate the performance of them. Then, the best performance forecast model will be used for sales forecasting.

  • Steps for evaluation of data modelling:

    1. Build the ARIMA Model and Seasonal ARIMA Model using the same times series as Holt-Winters model.

    2. Perform forecasting by ARIMA Model and Seasonal ARIMA Model

    3. Accuracy measures for Holt-Winters, ARIMA and Seasonal ARIMA forecast models. One of most commonly used scale-dependent measures is based on the Root mean squared error (RMSE). When comparing forecast methods applied to a single time series, or to several time series with the same units, the RMSE is popular as it is easy to both understand and compute.

    4. The forecast model with smaller RMSE value is better. Choose that forecast model for sales forecasting.

      Figure: Overview of Time Series Forecast Error Metrics. Source: https://towardsdatascience.com/time-series-forecast-error-metrics-you-should-know-cc88b8c67f27

5.1.4.2 Perform forecasting by ARIMA Model and Seasonal ARIMA Model

  • Step 2. Perform forecasting by ARIMA Model and Seasonal ARIMA Model. We forecast sales on the next following 179 days (same as test data) from the training data, which is exactly we have done by Holt-Winters model in above section.
#perform forecasting
arima_forecast <- forecast(arima, level=0, h=179)
sarima_forecast <- forecast(sarima, level=0, h=179)

5.1.4.3 Accuracy measures

  • Step 3. Accuracy measures for forecast models.

  • The measures calculated by accuracy(x) function are:

    1. ME: Mean Error
    2. RMSE: Root Mean Squared Error
    3. MAE: Mean Absolute Error
    4. MPE: Mean Percentage Error
    5. MAPE: Mean Absolute Percentage Error
    6. MASE: Mean Absolute Scaled Error
    7. ACF1: Autocorrelation of errors at lag 1.
library("forecast")
# Accuracy measures for a forecast model by accuracy() function
#syntax of accuracy(x)
#x: An object of class “forecast” containing forecasts.
accuracy(arima_forecast)
##                     ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set -396.5471 11661.67 8156.845 -22.51886 41.33769 0.5601757
##                     ACF1
## Training set -0.00298769
accuracy(sarima_forecast)
##                     ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE     MAPE      MASE       ACF1
## Training set -375.9069 11813.86 8273.384 -22.8823 41.88888 0.5681792 0.07669063
accuracy(HW_forecast)
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE       ACF1
## Training set 53.80286 10946.59 6448.577 -19.44353 42.89914 0.4428595 0.01334179

5.1.4.4 Choose better forecast model for sales forecasting.

  • Step 4. The forecast model with smaller RMSE value is better. Holt-Winters forecast model is better. We choose Holt-Winters model for sales forecasting with our data.
accuracy_arima <- accuracy(arima_forecast)
accuracy_sarima <- accuracy(sarima_forecast)
accuracy_HW <- accuracy(HW_forecast)
#compare the RMSE values between the 3 forecast models. Holt-Winters forecast model is better.
accuracy_arima["Training set","RMSE"]  
## [1] 11661.67
accuracy_sarima["Training set","RMSE"]  
## [1] 11813.86
accuracy_HW["Training set","RMSE"]  
## [1] 10946.59

df.retail <- read.csv(file = 'R_DA_Data_online_retail_II_clean.csv', header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE, strip.white = TRUE, sep = ",")
